node.text:
“That’s one of the benefits of a program that’s been running for over 30 years: the incredible amount of experience and expertise.”

After Hubble ran into a payload computer issue on June 13, team members new and old worked to recover the telescope. Science operations resumed on July 17.

Their efforts helped ensure that Hubble’s exploration of the universe is far from over. Read more at the link in our bio!

#NASA #Hubble #video #telescope #news #science #astronomy

node.title: NASA Returns Hubble to Science Operations

node.text:
Dark matter is the “invisible glue” that holds the universe together.

All galaxies seem to be dominated by it, but Hubble observations of an oddball galaxy lacking dark matter are challenging theories of galaxy formation.

Learn more about this cosmic mystery at the link in our bio!

node.title: Mystery of Galaxy’s Missing Dark Matter Deepens

Fast radio bursts (FRBs for short) are extraordinary events that generate as much energy in a thousandth of a second as the Sun does in an entire year!

Hubble is helping astronomers learn more about these fascinating bursts, and even tracked down the locations of five FRBs.

Learn more at the link in our bio!

✨ Our galaxy is home to at least 200 billion stars.

node.text:
This planet may have lost one atmosphere, but gained another!

Hubble studied an exoplanet (a planet outside our solar system) 41 light-years away. Its original atmosphere is believed to have been lost due to the intense radiation of the star it orbits, but this rocky exoplanet might have a second one through volcanic activity.

Read more at the link in our bio!

The star cluster in this #HubbleFriday image has been known by many names: Dun 538, H 3688, and Pismis 25.

Why? Different astronomers “rediscovered” it multiple times. But these days, it’s known reliably as simply NGC 6380 (NGC = New General Catalogue).

NGC 6380 is a globular cluster, which is a spherical group of stars bound together by gravity. Globular clusters often contain some of the oldest stars in their galaxies!

This cluster is located 35,000 light-years from Earth, though the very bright star at the top of the image is a lot closer at only 4,000 light-years away.

Discover more at the link in our bio!

Ever heard of a “flocculent” galaxy? You’re looking at one.

This #HubbleClassic view shows the galaxy NGC 3521, which is classified as a flocculent spiral galaxy because it doesn’t have clearly defined arms, leading to a soft, woolly appearance!

NGC 3521 is located about 26 million light-years away and is found in the constellation Leo.

Two enormous galaxies steal the show in this spectacular #HubbleFriday image.

The galaxy on the left is a lenticular galaxy named 2MASX J03193743+4137580. The spiral galaxy on the right is (much more simply) named UGC 2665.

Both galaxies lie approximately 350 million light-years from Earth, and form part of the huge Perseus galaxy cluster.

This glimpse of the Crab Nebula’s “beating heart” was released #OTD 5️⃣ years ago!

The neutron star at the very center of the Crab Nebula has about the same mass as the Sun but compressed into an incredibly dense sphere that is only a few miles across.

Spinning 30 times a second, the neutron star shoots out detectable beams of energy that make it look like it's pulsating.

Now introducing… a new type of supernova! 💥

With the help of Hubble, astronomers found evidence supporting the existence of a hypothesized type of exploding star called an electron-capture supernova.

The white dot on the right of this image shows supernova SN 2018zd, observed in 2018, which matches criteria for an electron-capture supernova!

Find out more at the link in our bio.

Ready for the #FourthOfJuly weekend? 🇺🇸

This red, white, and blue #HubbleFriday image shows off the dazzling star cluster NGC 330.

At about 180,000 light-years away, NGC 330 contains a multitude of stars that are roughly the same age because they formed from the same cloud of gas and dust!

Journey through the cosmic circle of life 🌟

The spiral galaxy M83, also known as the Southern Pinwheel, resides 15 million light-years away in the constellation Hydra. 

Spread across 50,000 light-years, this stunning galactic mosaic features billions of stars at different stages of life. From star births to deaths, vibrant colors spread across this Hubble image showcase the various ages of stars in this galaxy. 

The rich magenta and blue colors indicate areas of recent star formation, with stars as young as a few million years old. The yellow or orange regions reveal stars up to 100 million years or older.

(Also... hi! This is Hubble's first Reel! What type of content do you want to see from us here? Let us know in the comments!)
